17. I would rather ſtroak you with the ſeather, then prick you with the pen; 

                     ••

                  cept to provoke you to good works, and to mind you of your danger. Indeed, I feared, at the time I wrote my laſt Book, that many of my worthy Brethren were falling;


               and I was (in my Epiſtle) ſomewhat earneſt to ſave them, and that, I hope, was all my Crime, and no more then Ingenuous perſons are willing to pardon.
